solutions.content:
Since we need a total mean of (m+n) elements in the array rolls[n+m], where 1<= rolls[i] <=6, equal to given `mean`.

Let rolls = [1,5,6], mean = 3, n = 4
we have, m (size of rolls) = 3
n = 4
therefore, length = m + n = 7

we know, mean = (rolls[0] + rolls[1] + ... + rolls[m+n-1]) / length
=> (sum of given m rolls + sum_of_n_missing numbers) / length = mean
=> (sum_m + sum_n) / (m+n) = mean
=> sum_n = mean * (m+n) - sum_m

putting the given values in the above equation we got something like given below.
sum_n = 3 * (3 + 4) - 12 = 9

Now, we need to find the `n` numbers whose sum is 9

```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> missingRolls(vector<int>& rolls, int mean, int n) {
        int sum_m = 0, m = rolls.size();
        for(auto val : rolls) {
            sum_m += val;
        }

        // we have to find the n numbers whose sum is 9
        int sum_n = (mean*(n+m)) - sum_m;

        vector<int> ans;

		// E.g. sum_n = 100, n = 7, 
		// We won't be able to get 7 numbers selecting between 1 to 6 whose sum will be 100
		// Even after selecting seven 6's we will end up having only sum of 42, but we need 100
		// so this case will result an empty array
        if(sum_n > 6*n) return ans;

		// E.g. sum_n = 2, n = 7, 
		// We won't be able to get 7 numbers selecting between 1 to 6 whose sum will be 2
		// so this case will also result an empty array
        if(sum_n < n) return ans;

		// sum_n = 9, n = 4, => val = 9/4 = 2
        int val = sum_n / n;

		// ans = [2, 2, 2, 2]
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) 
            ans.push_back(val);

		// rem = 9 % 4 = 1
        int rem = sum_n % n;

		// ans = [2+1, 2, 2, 2] = [3, 2, 2, 2]
        for(int i=0; i<rem; i++) 
            ans[i] += 1;

        return ans;
    }
};
```

