# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We are given with the mean of n + m observations, so by applying some math we can find the sum of all numbers and then find the numbers.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First we find the sum of all elements let denote it with sum. Now we are given with m elements so we can find the sum of remaining n elements.
Now if the sum of these n elements is less than n (not possible as minimum value of dice roll is 1) or greater than 6*n (not possible as maximum value of dice roll is 6) we return empty array.

After that we traverse through n and find by appropiate number by dividing sum by n.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n+m)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> missingRolls(vector<int>& rolls, int mean, int n) {
        int m = rolls.size();
        //find the sum of all elements
        long sum = 1L*mean*(n+m);

        //remove m elements sum
        for(int i =0; i<m; i++){
            sum -= rolls[i];
        }
        vector<int> res; 
        // if it is not possible to get sum return empty array
        if(sum < n || sum > 6*n) return res;

        //find appropiate elements
        while(n > 0){
            int x = sum/n;
            sum -= x;
            res.push_back(x);
            n--;
        } 
        return res;
    }
};
```

