# Approach
First we find out the sum we need in order to achieve the given mean.

Suppose;
```
Given observations = rolls = len(rolls) = 3, sum(rolls) = 7
Missing observations = 3
Mean = 4
Total observations = 6
```

Now; normally we calculate mean by;

    sum(observations) / len(observations) 

We use the same formula and apply here;

    (sum(rolls) + sum(missing_rolls)) / observations_total = mean

i.e 

    7 + sum(missing_rolls) / 6 = 4

    sum(missing_rolls) = 6*4 - 7
    sum(missing_rolls) = 17

now with this we calculate the mean;

    mean = sum(missing_rolls) / len(missing_rolls)


Now do some basic checks for checking the boundary of the rolls;

    if (mean) < 1 && mean > 6; return []

after these checks, we now just loop over the required elements array and keep on adding the ceiling of the mean;

```
requiredElements := make([]int, n)

for i, _ := range requiredElements {
    ceilMean := ceil(mean)
    requiredElements[i] = ceilMean

    // we subtract the ceilMean from the required sum
    // and decrease the number of elements we require

    missing_rolls_sum -= ceilMean
    n-=1
    mean = missing_rolls_sum / n
} 
```


