# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
to get a sum from n numbers, the best number would e it's average, like, from 4 numbers make 13, *13 / 4 is 3*, with an offest of 1 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Find the sum of missing observation,that is = `(mean * (n + rolls.size())) - sum(rolls)`.
2. If `toFindSum < n or toFindSum > 6 * n` then it's not possible, so return an empty array.
3. After this we only have to distribute missingSum to n elements. So i used below method:-
 - Assign `guess` i.e. `toFindSum / n` to every element of new array.
4. for offset, if `extra` i.e. `toFindSum % n` is not zero then, add 1 to number of guess times to every element of `missing`.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$ , output array is not considered
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> missingRolls(vector<int>& rolls, int mean, int n) {
        int sum = accumulate(rolls.begin(), rolls.end(), 0);
        int toFindSum = (mean * (n + rolls.size())) - sum;

        if(toFindSum > 6 * n || toFindSum < n)
            return {};

        int guess = toFindSum / n;
        vector<int> missing(n, guess);
        int extra = toFindSum % n;

        for(int i = 0; i < extra; ++i)
            missing[i] += 1;

        return missing;   
    }
};
```
